{"title_page": "Jonas K\u00e4llstr\u00f6m", "text_new": "{{Use dmy dates|date=April 2020}}\n{{Infobox football biography\n| name = Jonas K\u00e4llstr\u00f6m\n| image = \n| caption = \n| fullname = \n| birth_date = {{Birth date and age|1963|9|23|df=y}}\n| birth_place =\n| height = \n| position = [[Midfielder]]\n| currentclub = \n| clubnumber = \n| youthyears1 = |youthclubs1 = [[IFK Hedemora]]\n| years1 =  | clubs1 = [[Krylbo IF]] | caps1= | goals1=\n| years2 =1986  | clubs2 = [[S\u00e4ters IF]] | caps2= | goals2=\n| years3 =1987\u20131993  | clubs3 = [[IK Brage]] | caps3=  | goals3= \n| manageryears1 =  | managerclubs1 = [[S\u00e4ters IF]]\n| manageryears2 =  | managerclubs2 = [[Korsn\u00e4s IF Dam]] (assistant coach)\n}}\n\n'''Jonas K\u00e4llstr\u00f6m''' (born 23 September 1963) is a Swedish former [[association football|footballer]] who played as a [[midfielder]].<ref>{{Worldfootball.net|jonas-kaellstroem}}</ref> He made 98 [[Allsvenskan]] appearances for [[IK Brage]] and scored six goals. For [[IK Brage]], he also made two appearances in the [[1988\u201389 UEFA Cup]].<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.worldfootball.net/player_summary/jonas-kaellstroem/europa-league/2/|title=Jonas K\u00e4llstr\u00f6m &raquo; Club matches &raquo; Europa League|website=worldfootball.net}}</ref>\n\nHe is the brother of Swedish footballer [[Mikael K\u00e4llstr\u00f6m]]<ref>http://www.dn.se/arkiv/sport/allsvenskan-360</ref> and the uncle of Swedish international footballer [[Kim K\u00e4llstr\u00f6m]].\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Kallstrom, Jonas}}\n[[Category:Living people]]\n[[Category:1963 births]]\n[[Category:Association football midfielders]]\n[[Category:Swedish footballers]]\n[[Category:Allsvenskan players]]\n[[Category:IK Brage players]]\n", "text_old": "{{Infobox football biography\n| name = Jonas K\u00e4llstr\u00f6m\n| image = \n| caption = \n| fullname = \n| birth_date = {{Birth date and age|1963|9|23|df=y}}\n| birth_place =\n| height = \n| position =\n| currentclub = \n| clubnumber = \n| youthyears1 = |youthclubs1 = [[IFK Hedemora]]\n| years1 =  | clubs1 = [[Krylbo IF]] | caps1= | goals1=\n| years2 =1986  | clubs2 = [[S\u00e4ters IF]] | caps2= | goals2=\n| years3 =1987\u20131993  | clubs3 = [[IK Brage]] | caps3=  | goals3= \n| manageryears1 =  | managerclubs1 = [[S\u00e4ters IF]]\n| manageryears2 =  | managerclubs2 = [[Korsn\u00e4s IF Dam]] (assistant coach)\n}}\n\n'''Jonas K\u00e4llstr\u00f6m''' (born 23 September 1963<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.worldfootball.net/player_summary/jonas-kaellstroem/|title=Jonas K\u00e4llstr\u00f6m|website=worldfootball.net}}</ref>) is a Swedish former footballer. He made 98 [[Allsvenskan]] appearances for [[IK Brage]] and scored six goals. For [[IK Brage]], he also made two appearances in the [[1988\u201389 UEFA Cup]].<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.worldfootball.net/player_summary/jonas-kaellstroem/europa-league/2/|title=Jonas K\u00e4llstr\u00f6m &raquo; Club matches &raquo; Europa League|website=worldfootball.net}}</ref>\n\nHe is the brother of Swedish footballer [[Mikael K\u00e4llstr\u00f6m]].<ref>http://www.dn.se/arkiv/sport/allsvenskan-360</ref> He is the uncle of Swedish international footballer [[Kim K\u00e4llstr\u00f6m]].\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Kallstrom, Jonas}}\n[[Category:Swedish footballers]]\n[[Category:IK Brage players]]\n[[Category:Allsvenskan players]]\n[[Category:1963 births]]\n[[Category:Living people]]\n[[Category:Association footballers not categorized by position]]\n", "name_user": "Robby.is.on", "label": "safe", "comment": "Fix playing position category. Minor corrections.", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Jonas_K%C3%A4llstr%C3%B6m"}
{"title_page": "Lior Ashkenazi", "text_new": "{{short description|Israeli screen and stage actor|bot=PearBOT 5}}\n{{Infobox person\n| name           = Lior Ashkenazi\n| image          = Lior Ashkenazi, taken by Niv Calderon (cropped).jpg\n| caption         = Lior Ashkenazi in 2006\n| birth_date     = {{Birth date and age|1968|12|28}}\n| birth_place    = [[Ramat Gan]], [[Israel]]\n| occupation    = [[Actor]]\n| spouse         = Maya Amsellem\n| children       = 2\n}}\n'''Lior Ashkenazi''' ({{lang-he|\u05dc\u05d9\u05d0\u05d5\u05e8 \u05d0\u05e9\u05db\u05e0\u05d6\u05d9}}; born 28 December 1968) is an [[Israel]]i screen and stage actor.\n\n== Early life ==\nAshkenazi was born in [[Ramat Gan]], Israel, and grew up in its Neveh Yehoshua neighborhood. His parents are [[Sephardi Jews|Sephardi Jewish]] emigrants from [[Istanbul]], [[Turkey]], who moved to Israel in 1964.<ref>{{cite web|author=Culture |url=http://jewishjournal.com/culture/arts/232487/lior-ashkenazi-goes-international/ |title=Lior Ashkenazi Goes International |publisher=Jewishjournal.com |date=2018-03-28 |accessdate=2018-08-15}}</ref> His father, Shmuel, worked as a printer. His mother, Victoria, was a housewife. His parents spoke [[Judaeo-Spanish|Ladino]] at home, and it was his first language. At the age of 16, in the wake of problems in school, he moved to [[Kibbutz]] [[Regavim]].<ref name=\"haaretz.com\">[http://www.haaretz.com/the-naked-truth-1.8548 The Naked Truth, [[Haaretz]]]</ref>\n\nHe served as a paratrooper in the [[Israel Defense Forces]], serving in the [[Nahal Brigade]], serving in the territories during the [[First Intifada]].<ref name=star>[https://www.haaretz.com/1.4933412 Shooting Star] Haaretz. 18 August 2005</ref>\n\n== Career ==\nHe studied acting at [[Beit Zvi]]. After graduating in 1994, he worked for [[Habima]] and [[Beersheba Theater]]. He starred in many plays at [[Beit Lessin Theater]] under the direction of Zipi Pines, one of his teachers at Beit Zvi. He also appeared with the [[Cameri Theater]] in Tel Aviv, although Beit Lessin remained his home base.<ref name=\"haaretz.com\"/> His breakout role came in ''[[Late Marriage]]'' alongside [[Ronit Elkabetz]] in 2001.<ref name=star/>\n\nIn 2016 he appeared alongside Hollywood actor, [[Richard Gere]] in the critically acclaimed political drama, ''[[Norman: The Moderate Rise and Tragic Fall of a New York Fixer]]''.<ref>[https://www.haaretz.com/israel-news/culture/movies/.premium-hollywood-press-praises-israeli-films-norman-past-life-1.5437736 Hollywood Press Praises New Israeli Films 'Norman,' 'Past Life'] Haaretz. 18 September 2016</ref> Ashkenazi won an [[Ophir Award]] for Best Lead Actor<ref>[https://www.haaretz.com/israel-news/foxtrot-wins-highest-award-at-israeli-oscars-1.5452354 To Culture Minster's Horror, 'Foxtrot' Wins Highest Award at 'Israeli Oscars'] Haaretz. 19 September 2017</ref> for his performance in  the 2017 film, ''[[Foxtrot (2017 film)|Foxtrot]]'', Israel's entry for the [[Academy Award for Best Foreign Language Film|Best Foreign Language Film]] at the [[90th Academy Awards]].<ref name=\"Israel\">{{Cite news|url=https://variety.com/2017/film/awards/israel-foxtrot-oscar-foreign-language-ophir-award-1202563877/|title=Israel\u2019s \u2018Foxtrot\u2019 Sweeps Ophir Awards to Become Country\u2019s Oscar Entry|work=[[Variety (magazine)|Variety]]|publisher=[[Penske Business Media]]|first=Debra|last=Kamin|date=19 September 2017|accessdate=19 September 2017}}</ref>\n\nIn November 2018 Asheknazi appeared in [[Shakespeare]]'s ''[[The Tempest]]'', a joint production between the [[Old Globe Theatre]] and the [[Los Angeles Philharmonic]].<ref>[https://www.haaretz.com/israel-news/culture/.premium-israeli-actor-lior-ashkenazi-to-play-lead-role-in-l-a-shakespeare-play-1.6472939 Israeli Actor Lior Ashkenazi to Play Lead Role in L.A. Shakespeare Play] Haaretz. 16 September 2018</ref>\n\nIn 2019 Ashkenazi appeared in [[HBO]]'s show ''[[Our Boys (miniseries)|Our Boys]]'', an American-Israeli series.<ref name=\"Cast\">{{cite web |url=https://www.hbo.com/our-boys/cast-and-crew |title=Our Boys Cast |publisher=[[HBO]] |accessdate=August 21, 2019}}</ref>\n\n== Personal life ==\nAshkenazi was first married to actress Shira Farber, with whom he had his first daughter. After his divorce, he had a relationship with playwright and screenwriter [[Sigal Avin]]. In December 2011, he married producer Maya Amsellem. They had a daughter in August 2012.<ref name=\"haaretz.com\"/>\n\n==Filmography ==\n=== Film ===\n{| class=\"wikitable sortable\"\n|-\n! Year\n! Title\n! Role\n! Notes\n|-\n| 1996\n| ''[[Pocahontas (1995 film)|Pocahontas]]''\n| Kocoum (voice)\n| Hebrew dub\n|-\n| 1998\n| ''[[Mulan (1998 film)|Mulan]]''\n| Captain Li Shang (voice)\n| Hebrew dub\n|-\n| 1999\n| ''[[Tarzan (1999 film)|Tarzan]]''\n| Adult Tarzan (voice)\n| Hebrew dub\n|-\n| 2001\n| ''[[Late Marriage]]'' (''Hatuna Meuheret'')\n| Zaza\n|\n|-\n| 2003\n| ''[[Rutenberg (film)|Rutenberg]]'' (''Ish HaHashmal'', ''Electricity Man'')\n| Leonard\n|\n|-\n| rowspan=2 | 2004\n| ''[[Walk on Water (film)|Walk on Water]]'' (''Lalechet Al HaMaim'')\n| Eyal\n|\n|-\n| ''[[Home on the Range (2004 film)|Home on the Range]]''\n| Buck Horse (voice)\n| Hebrew dub\n|-\n| 2005\n| ''[[Mulan II]]''\n| Captain Lee Shang (voice)\n| Hebrew dub\n|-\n| 2006\n| ''[[The Bubble (2006 film)|The Bubble]]'' (''HaBuah'')\n| Himself\n| Cameo\n|-\n| rowspan=2 | 2008\n| ''[[Bolt (2008 film)|Bolt]]''\n| Bolt (voice)\n| Hebrew dub\n|-\n| ''[[Hello Goodbye (film)|Hello Goodbye]]''\n| Yossi\n| French film\n|-\n| 2009\n| ''[[Ultimatum (2009 film)|Ultimatum]]''\n| Gil\n| Italian film\n|-\n| 2010\n| ''[[Rabies (2010 film)|Rabies]]'' (''Kalevet'')\n| Danny\n| The first horror feature ever from Israel<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.jfedpgh.org/rabies.aspx |title=Archived copy |accessdate=2013-02-06 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20120510161826/http://jfedpgh.org/rabies.aspx |archivedate=2012-05-10 }} JFilm Festival presents: Rabies (Winner - Best Feature - Mile High Horror Film Festival)</ref>\n|-\n| 2011\n| ''[[Footnote (film)|Footnote]]''\n| Uriel Shkolnik\n|\n|-\n| rowspan=2 | 2012\n| ''Karon'' \n| Michael\n| Short film\n|-\n| ''[[Yossi (film)|Yossi]]''\n| Moti\n|\n|-\n| 2013\n| ''[[Big Bad Wolves]]''<ref>[http://www.facebook.com/pages/Big-Bad-Wolves-%D7%9E%D7%99-%D7%9E%D7%A4%D7%97%D7%93-%D7%9E%D7%94%D7%96%D7%90%D7%91-%D7%94%D7%A8%D7%A2/217917485014382 ''Big Bad Wolves'' official facebook]</ref><ref>{{IMDb title|2309224|Big Bad Wolves}}</ref>\n| Micki\n|\n|-\n| 2014\n| ''[[The Dune (film)|The Dune]]''\n| Hanoch\n| French fim\n|-\n| 2016\n| ''[[Norman: The Moderate Rise and Tragic Fall of a New York Fixer]]''\n| Micha Eshel\n|\n|-\n| 2017\n|''[[Foxtrot (2017 film)|Foxtrot]]''\n| Michael Feldmann\n|\n|-\n| 2018\n|''[[7 Days in Entebbe]]''\n|  [[Yitzhak Rabin]]\n|\n|-\n| 2019\n|''[[My Zoe]]''\n|\n| Post-production\n|}\n\n=== Television ===\n{| class=\"wikitable sortable\"\n|-\n! Year\n! Title\n! Role\n! Notes\n|-\n| 2005\n| ''[[BeTipul]]''\n| Yadin Yerushalmi\n|\n|-\n| 2012\n|''[[Nesuuim plus]]''\n| Shuky Avrahami\n| Hebrew version of [[Married with children]] (his character based on [[Al Bundy]]\n|-\n| 2013\n| ''[[The Missionary (TV pilot)|The Missionary]]''\n| Yonatan Gall\n| TV pilot\n|-\n| 2016\n| ''Ikaron HaHachlafa''\n| Atlas\n| Lead role\n|}\n\n== Awards and nominations ==\n{| class=\"wikitable\" style=\"width:100%;\"\n|-\n! width=5%| Year\n! style=\"width:25%;\"| Award\n! style=\"width:30%;\"| Category\n! style=\"width:25%;\"| Nominated work\n! style=\"width:10%;\"| Result\n! width=5%| {{Abbr|Ref.|Reference(s)}}\n|-\n| rowspan=2 | 2001 || rowspan=5 | [[Israeli Film Academy]] || Best Actor || ''[[Late Marriage (film)|Late Marriage]]'' || {{won}} || style=\"text-align:center;\"| \n|-\n| Best Supporting Actor ||  ''[[Rutenberg (film)|Rutenberg]]'' (''Ish HaHashmal'') || {{nom}} || style=\"text-align:center;\"| \n|-\n| 2004 || Best Actor || ''[[Walk on Water (film)|Walk on Water]]'' || {{nom}} || style=\"text-align:center;\"|<ref>[http://www.omanoot.com/Artist-58,1257-Lior-Ashkenazi.aspx Lior Ashkenazi, Biography]. Omanoot  {{webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20110111054243/http://www.omanoot.com/Artist-58%2C1257-Lior-Ashkenazi.aspx |date=January 11, 2011 }}</ref>\n|-\n| 2011 || Best Supporting Actor || ''[[Footnote (film)|Footnote]]'' || {{won}} || style=\"text-align:center;\"|\n|-\n| 2017 || Best Actor || ''[[Foxtrot (2017 film)|Foxtrot]]'' || {{won}} || style=\"text-align:center;\"|\n|-\n| 2015 || [[Fangoria Chainsaw Awards]] || [[Fangoria Chainsaw Award for Best Actor|Best Actor]] || ''[[Big Bad Wolves]]'' || {{nom}} || style=\"text-align:center;\"| <ref>[http://www.fangoria.com/new/for-your-consideration-the-2015-chainsaw-award-nominees-for-best-actor/ For Your Consideration: The 2015 Chainsaw Award Nominees for Best Actor!]</ref>\n|}\n\n== References ==\n{{reflist}}\n\n== External links ==\n{{common|Category:Lior Ashkenazi|Lior Ashkenazi}}\n* {{IMDb name|id=0038988|name=Lior Askenazi}}\n\n{{Authority control}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Ashkenazi, Lior}}\n[[Category:Israeli male film actors]]\n[[Category:Israeli male voice actors]]\n[[Category:People from Ramat Gan]]\n[[Category:Living people]]\n[[Category:1969 births]]\n[[Category:Israeli people of Turkish-Jewish descent]]\n[[Category:Sephardi Jews]]\n[[Category:Mizrahi Jews]]\n", "text_old": "{{short description|Israeli screen and stage actor|bot=PearBOT 5}}\n{{Infobox person\n| name           = Lior Ashkenazi\n| image          = Lior Ashkenazi, taken by Niv Calderon (cropped).jpg\n| caption         = Lior Ashkenazi in 2006\n| birth_date     = {{Birth date and age|1968|12|28}}\n| birth_place    = [[Ramat Gan]], [[Israel]]\n| occupation    = [[Actor]]\n| spouse         = Maya Amsellem\n| children       = 2\n}}\n'''Lior Ashkenazi''' ({{lang-he|\u05dc\u05d9\u05d0\u05d5\u05e8 \u05d0\u05e9\u05db\u05e0\u05d6\u05d9}}; born 28 December 1968) is an [[Israel]]i screen and stage actor.\n\n== Early life ==\nAshkenazi was born in [[Ramat Gan]], Israel, and grew up in its Neveh Yehoshua neighborhood. His parents are [[Sephardi Jews|Sephardi Jewish]] emigrants from [[Istanbul]], [[Turkey]], who moved to Israel in 1964.<ref>{{cite web|author=Culture |url=http://jewishjournal.com/culture/arts/232487/lior-ashkenazi-goes-international/ |title=Lior Ashkenazi Goes International |publisher=Jewishjournal.com |date=2018-03-28 |accessdate=2018-08-15}}</ref> His father, Shmuel, worked as a printer. His mother, Victoria, was a housewife. His parents spoke [[Judaeo-Spanish|Ladino]] at home, and it was his first language. At the age of 16, in the wake of problems in school, he moved to [[Kibbutz]] [[Regavim]].<ref name=\"haaretz.com\">[http://www.haaretz.com/the-naked-truth-1.8548 The Naked Truth, [[Haaretz]]]</ref>\n\nHe served as a paratrooper in the [[Israel Defense Forces]], serving in the [[Nahal Brigade]], serving in the territories during the [[First Intifada]].<ref name=star>[https://www.haaretz.com/1.4933412 Shooting Star] Haaretz. 18 August 2005</ref>\n\n== Career ==\nHe studied acting at [[Beit Zvi]]. After graduating in 1994, he worked for [[Habima]] and [[Beersheba Theater]]. He starred in many plays at [[Beit Lessin Theater]] under the direction of Zipi Pines, one of his teachers at Beit Zvi. He also appeared with the [[Cameri Theater]] in Tel Aviv, although Beit Lessin remained his home base.<ref name=\"haaretz.com\"/> His breakout role came in ''[[Late Marriage]]'' alongside [[Ronit Elkabetz]] in 2001.<ref name=star/>\n\nIn 2016 he appeared alongside Hollywood actor, [[Richard Gere]] in the critically acclaimed political drama, ''[[Norman: The Moderate Rise and Tragic Fall of a New York Fixer]]''.<ref>[https://www.haaretz.com/israel-news/culture/movies/.premium-hollywood-press-praises-israeli-films-norman-past-life-1.5437736 Hollywood Press Praises New Israeli Films 'Norman,' 'Past Life'] Haaretz. 18 September 2016</ref> Ashkenazi won an [[Ophir Award]] for Best Lead Actor<ref>[https://www.haaretz.com/israel-news/foxtrot-wins-highest-award-at-israeli-oscars-1.5452354 To Culture Minster's Horror, 'Foxtrot' Wins Highest Award at 'Israeli Oscars'] Haaretz. 19 September 2017</ref> for his performance in  the 2017 film, ''[[Foxtrot (2017 film)|Foxtrot]]'', Israel's entry for the [[Academy Award for Best Foreign Language Film|Best Foreign Language Film]] at the [[90th Academy Awards]].<ref name=\"Israel\">{{Cite news|url=https://variety.com/2017/film/awards/israel-foxtrot-oscar-foreign-language-ophir-award-1202563877/|title=Israel\u2019s \u2018Foxtrot\u2019 Sweeps Ophir Awards to Become Country\u2019s Oscar Entry|work=[[Variety (magazine)|Variety]]|publisher=[[Penske Business Media]]|first=Debra|last=Kamin|date=19 September 2017|accessdate=19 September 2017}}</ref>\n\nIn November 2018 Asheknazi appeared in [[Shakespeare]]'s ''[[The Tempest]]'', a joint production between the [[Old Globe Theatre]] and the [[Los Angeles Philharmonic]].<ref>[https://www.haaretz.com/israel-news/culture/.premium-israeli-actor-lior-ashkenazi-to-play-lead-role-in-l-a-shakespeare-play-1.6472939 Israeli Actor Lior Ashkenazi to Play Lead Role in L.A. Shakespeare Play] Haaretz. 16 September 2018</ref>\n\nIn 2019 Asheknazi appeared in [[HBO]]'s show ''[[Our Boys (miniseries)|Our Boys]]'', an American-Israeli series.<ref name=\"Cast\">{{cite web |url=https://www.hbo.com/our-boys/cast-and-crew |title=Our Boys Cast |publisher=[[HBO]] |accessdate=August 21, 2019}}</ref>\n\n== Personal life ==\nAshkenazi was first married to actress Shira Farber, with whom he had his first daughter. After his divorce, he had a relationship with playwright and screenwriter [[Sigal Avin]]. In December 2011, he married producer Maya Amsellem. They had a daughter in August 2012.<ref name=\"haaretz.com\"/>\n\n==Filmography ==\n=== Film ===\n{| class=\"wikitable sortable\"\n|-\n! Year\n! Title\n! Role\n! Notes\n|-\n| 1996\n| ''[[Pocahontas (1995 film)|Pocahontas]]''\n| Kocoum (voice)\n