se and Tragic Fall of a New York Fixer]]''\n| Micha Eshel\n|\n|-\n| 2017\n|''[[Foxtrot (2017 film)|Foxtrot]]''\n| Michael Feldmann\n|\n|-\n| 2018\n|''[[7 Days in Entebbe]]''\n|  [[Yitzhak Rabin]]\n|\n|-\n| 2019\n|''[[My Zoe]]''\n|\n| Post-production\n|}\n\n=== Television ===\n{| class=\"wikitable sortable\"\n|-\n! Year\n! Title\n! Role\n! Notes\n|-\n| 2005\n| ''[[BeTipul]]''\n| Yadin Yerushalmi\n|\n|-\n| 2012\n|''[[Nesuuim plus]]''\n| Shuky Avrahami\n| Hebrew version of [[Married with children]] (his character based on [[Al Bundy]]\n|-\n| 2013\n| ''[[The Missionary (TV pilot)|The Missionary]]''\n| Yonatan Gall\n| TV pilot\n|-\n| 2016\n| ''Ikaron HaHachlafa''\n| Atlas\n| Lead role\n|}\n\n== Awards and nominations ==\n{| class=\"wikitable\" style=\"width:100%;\"\n|-\n! width=5%| Year\n! style=\"width:25%;\"| Award\n! style=\"width:30%;\"| Category\n! style=\"width:25%;\"| Nominated work\n! style=\"width:10%;\"| Result\n! width=5%| {{Abbr|Ref.|Reference(s)}}\n|-\n| rowspan=2 | 2001 || rowspan=5 | [[Israeli Film Academy]] || Best Actor || ''[[Late Marriage (film)|Late Marriage]]'' || {{won}} || style=\"text-align:center;\"| \n|-\n| Best Supporting Actor ||  ''[[Rutenberg (film)|Rutenberg]]'' (''Ish HaHashmal'') || {{nom}} || style=\"text-align:center;\"| \n|-\n| 2004 || Best Actor || ''[[Walk on Water (film)|Walk on Water]]'' || {{nom}} || style=\"text-align:center;\"|<ref>[http://www.omanoot.com/Artist-58,1257-Lior-Ashkenazi.aspx Lior Ashkenazi, Biography]. Omanoot  {{webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20110111054243/http://www.omanoot.com/Artist-58%2C1257-Lior-Ashkenazi.aspx |date=January 11, 2011 }}</ref>\n|-\n| 2011 || Best Supporting Actor || ''[[Footnote (film)|Footnote]]'' || {{won}} || style=\"text-align:center;\"|\n|-\n| 2017 || Best Actor || ''[[Foxtrot (2017 film)|Foxtrot]]'' || {{won}} || style=\"text-align:center;\"|\n|-\n| 2015 || [[Fangoria Chainsaw Awards]] || [[Fangoria Chainsaw Award for Best Actor|Best Actor]] || ''[[Big Bad Wolves]]'' || {{nom}} || style=\"text-align:center;\"| <ref>[http://www.fangoria.com/new/for-your-consideration-the-2015-chainsaw-award-nominees-for-best-actor/ For Your Consideration: The 2015 Chainsaw Award Nominees for Best Actor!]</ref>\n|}\n\n== References ==\n{{reflist}}\n\n== External links ==\n{{common|Category:Lior Ashkenazi|Lior Ashkenazi}}\n* {{IMDb name|id=0038988|name=Lior Askenazi}}\n\n{{Authority control}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Ashkenazi, Lior}}\n[[Category:Israeli male film actors]]\n[[Category:Israeli male voice actors]]\n[[Category:People from Ramat Gan]]\n[[Category:Living people]]\n[[Category:1969 births]]\n[[Category:Israeli people of Turkish-Jewish descent]]\n[[Category:Sephardi Jews]]\n[[Category:Mizrahi Jews]]\n", "name_user": "Bellowhead678", "label": "safe", "comment": "Asheknazi->Ashkenazi -Fix a typo in one click", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Lior_Ashkenazi"}
{"title_page": "Sanity", "text_new": "<!-- Please do not remove or change this AfD message until the discussion has been closed. -->\n{{Article for deletion/dated|page=Sanity|timestamp=20200401194223|year=2020|month=April|day=1|substed=yes}}\n<!-- Once discussion is closed, please place on talk page: {{Old AfD multi|page=Sanity|date=1 April 2020|result='''keep'''}} -->\n<!-- End of AfD message, feel free to edit beyond this point -->\n{{redirect|Sound mind|the phrase \"sound mind in a sound body\"|Mens sana in corpore sano}}\n{{other uses|Sanity (disambiguation)}}\n\n'''Sanity''' (from {{lang-la|s\u0101nit\u0101s}}) refers to the soundness, [[rationality]], and [[health]] of the [[human]] [[mind]], as opposed to [[insanity]]. A person is sane if they are [[Rationality|rational]]. In [[modern society]], the term has become exclusively [[synonym]]ous with '''''compos mentis''''' ({{lang-la|compos}}, having mastery of, and {{lang-la|mentis}}, mind), in contrast with ''[[non compos mentis]]'', or [[insanity]], meaning troubled conscience. A sane mind is nowadays considered healthy both from its analytical - once called ''rational'' - and emotional aspects.<ref>{{cite journal|last=Anderson|first=Steven W.|author2=Antoine Bechara|author3=Hanna Damasio|author4=Daniel Tranel|author5=Antonio R. Damasio|title=Impairment of social and moral behavior related to early damage in human prefrontal cortex|journal=Department of Neurology, Division of Behavioral Neurology and Cognitive Neuroscience, The University of Iowa College of Medicine, Iowa City, Iowa 52242, USA|date=1999|url=http://saki.caltech.edu/biCNS217/PDFs/Anderson1999.pdf|url-status=dead|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20140518134726/http://saki.caltech.edu/biCNS217/PDFs/Anderson1999.pdf|archive-date=2014-05-18|df=}}</ref> According to the writer, [[G. K. Chesterton]],<ref>Chesterton, G. K. 2002. ''The Outline of Sanity''. IHS Press</ref> sanity involves wholeness, whereas insanity implies narrowness and brokenness.\n\n==Psychiatry and psychology==\n[[Alfred Korzybski]] proposed a theory of sanity in his [[general semantics]]. He believed sanity was tied to the structural fit or lack of thereof, of what is going on in the world. He imposed this notion in a [[Map/territory relation|map-territory analogy]]: \"A [[map]] ''is not'' the territory it represents, but, if correct, it has a \"similar structure\" to the territory, which accounts for its [[usefulness]].\"<ref>[http://www.doyletics.com/art/sciencea.htm Science and Sanity] by Alfred Korzybski</ref> Given that science continually seeks to adjust its theories structurally to fit the facts, i.e., improves its maps to fit the territory, and thus advances more rapidly than any other field, he believed that the key to understanding sanity would be found in the study of the methods of science (and the study of structure as revealed by science). The adoption of a scientific outlook and attitude of continual adjustment by the individual toward their assumptions was the way, so he claimed. In other words, there were \"factors of sanity to be found in the physico-mathematical [[scientific method|methods of science]].\" He also stressed that sanity requires the awareness that \"whatever you say a thing is, it is not\"<ref>Korzybski, A. 2010. ''Selections from Science and Sanity''. The New Non-Aristotelian Library, p. VIII.</ref> because anything expressed through language is not the reality it refers to: language is like a map, and the map is not the territory. The territory, or reality, remains unnamable, unspeakable, and mysterious. Hence, the widespread assumption that we can grasp reality through language involves a degree of insanity.\n\nPsychiatrist [[Philip S. Graven]] suggested the term \"un-sane\" to describe a condition that is not exactly ''insane'', but not quite ''sane'' either.<ref>[http://www.neurosemantics.com/nlp-critiques/when-ecology-does-not-count When Ecology Does Not Count: Checking the Ecology of The Ecology Check] by L. Michael Hall, Ph.D.</ref>\n\nIn ''The Sane Society'', [[1955 in literature|published in 1955]], psychologist [[Erich Fromm]] proposed that not just individuals, but entire societies \"may be lacking in sanity.\" Fromm argued that one of the most deceptive features of social life involves \"consensual validation\":<ref>[http://www.vault-co.com/index.php?p=826_consensual_validation Consensual validation] at vault-co.com {{dead link|date=June 2016|bot=medic}}{{cbignore|bot=medic}}</ref>\n<blockquote>It is naively assumed that the fact that the majority of people share certain ideas or feelings proves the validity of these ideas and feelings. Nothing is further from the truth... Just as there is a ''[[folie \u00e0 deux]]'' there is a ''folie \u00e0 millions''. The fact that millions of people share the same [[vice]]s does not make these vices virtues, the fact that they share so many errors does not make the errors to be truths, and the fact that millions of people share the same form of mental pathology does not make these people sane.<ref>Fromm, Erich. ''The Sane Society'', Routledge, 1955, pp.14\u201315.</ref></blockquote>\n\n== Law ==\nIn [[criminal law|criminal]] and [[mental health law]], sanity is a [[legal term]] denoting that an individual is of sound mind and therefore can bear legal [[Moral responsibility|responsibility]] for their [[Action (philosophy)|actions]]. The official legal term is ''compos mentis''. It is generally defined in terms of the [[wikt:lack|absence]] of insanity (''[[non compos mentis]]'').  It is not a [[medical term]], although the opinions of [[Expert witness|medical expert]]s are often important in making a legal [[Case law|decision]] as to whether someone is sane or insane. It is also not the same concept as [[mental illness]].  One can be acting under profound mental illness and yet be sane, and one can also be [[Court order|ruled]] insane without an underlying mental illness.{{citation needed|date=December 2010}}\n\nLegal definitions of sanity have been little explored by science and medicine, as the concentration has been on illness.{{Citation needed|date=February 2011}} It remains entirely impossible to prove sanity. Furthermore, as Korzybski<ref>Korzybski, A. 2010. ''Selections from Science and Sanity''. The New Non-Aristotelian Library.</ref> has pointed out repeatedly, insanity to various degrees is widespread in the general population, which includes many people that are considered mentally fit in medical and legal terms. In this connection, Erich Fromm<ref>Fromm, Erich. 1955/1990. ''The Sane Society''.</ref> referred to the \"pathology of normalcy,\" while [[David Cooper (psychiatrist)|David Cooper]] proposed that normality was opposed to both madness and sanity.<ref>D Cooper, ''The Death of the Family'' (Penguin 1971) p. 12</ref>\n\n==Literary views==\n*[[J. R. R. Tolkien]] warns us that \"of his own sanity no man may securely judge.\"<ref>Quoted in T A Shippey, ''The Road to Middle Earth'' (London 1992) p. 293</ref>\n\n==See also==\n{{Wikiquote}}\n{{Wiktionary|sane|sanity}}\n* [[George Eman Vaillant]]\n* [[Insanity defense]]\n* [[Rationalism]]\n* [[Sanism]]\n* [[Self-actualisation]]\n\n==References==\n{{More citations needed|date=December 2010}}\n{{Reflist}}\n\n[[Category:Mental health law]]\n[[Category:General semantics]]\n", "text_old": "{{redirect|Sound mind|the phrase \"sound mind in a sound body\"|Mens sana in corpore sano}}\n{{other uses|Sanity (disambiguation)}}\n\n'''Sanity''' (from {{lang-la|s\u0101nit\u0101s}}) refers to the soundness, [[rationality]], and [[health]] of the [[human]] [[mind]], as opposed to [[insanity]]. A person is sane if they are [[Rationality|rational]]. In [[modern society]], the term has become exclusively [[synonym]]ous with '''''compos mentis''''' ({{lang-la|compos}}, having mastery of, and {{lang-la|mentis}}, mind), in contrast with ''[[non compos mentis]]'', or [[insanity]], meaning troubled conscience. A sane mind is nowadays considered healthy both from its analytical - once called ''rational'' - and emotional aspects.<ref>{{cite journal|last=Anderson|first=Steven W.|author2=Antoine Bechara|author3=Hanna Damasio|author4=Daniel Tranel|author5=Antonio R. Damasio|title=Impairment of social and moral behavior related to early damage in human prefrontal cortex|journal=Department of Neurology, Division of Behavioral Neurology and Cognitive Neuroscience, The University of Iowa College of Medicine, Iowa City, Iowa 52242, USA|date=1999|url=http://saki.caltech.edu/biCNS217/PDFs/Anderson1999.pdf|url-status=dead|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20140518134726/http://saki.caltech.edu/biCNS217/PDFs/Anderson1999.pdf|archive-date=2014-05-18|df=}}</ref> According to the writer, [[G. K. Chesterton]],<ref>Chesterton, G. K. 2002. ''The Outline of Sanity''. IHS Press</ref> sanity involves wholeness, whereas insanity implies narrowness and brokenness.\n\n==Psychiatry and psychology==\n[[Alfred Korzybski]] proposed a theory of sanity in his [[general semantics]]. He believed sanity was tied to the structural fit or lack of thereof, of what is going on in the world. He imposed this notion in a [[Map/territory relation|map-territory analogy]]: \"A [[map]] ''is not'' the territory it represents, but, if correct, it has a \"similar structure\" to the territory, which accounts for its [[usefulness]].\"<ref>[http://www.doyletics.com/art/sciencea.htm Science and Sanity] by Alfred Korzybski</ref> Given that science continually seeks to adjust its theories structurally to fit the facts, i.e., improves its maps to fit the territory, and thus advances more rapidly than any other field, he believed that the key to understanding sanity would be found in the study of the methods of science (and the study of structure as revealed by science). The adoption of a scientific outlook and attitude of continual adjustment by the individual toward their assumptions was the way, so he claimed. In other words, there were \"factors of sanity to be found in the physico-mathematical [[scientific method|methods of science]].\" He also stressed that sanity requires the awareness that \"whatever you say a thing is, it is not\"<ref>Korzybski, A. 2010. ''Selections from Science and Sanity''. The New Non-Aristotelian Library, p. VIII.</ref> because anything expressed through language is not the reality it refers to: language is like a map, and the map is not the territory. The territory, or reality, remains unnamable, unspeakable, and mysterious. Hence, the widespread assumption that we can grasp reality through language involves a degree of insanity.\n\nPsychiatrist [[Philip S. Graven]] suggested the term \"un-sane\" to describe a condition that is not exactly ''insane'', but not quite ''sane'' either.<ref>[http://www.neurosemantics.com/nlp-critiques/when-ecology-does-not-count When Ecology Does Not Count: Checking the Ecology of The Ecology Check] by L. Michael Hall, Ph.D.</ref>\n\nIn ''The Sane Society'', [[1955 in literature|published in 1955]], psychologist [[Erich Fromm]] proposed that not just individuals, but entire societies \"may be lacking in sanity.\" Fromm argued that one of the most deceptive features of social life involves \"consensual validation\":<ref>[http://www.vault-co.com/index.php?p=826_consensual_validation Consensual validation] at vault-co.com {{dead link|date=June 2016|bot=medic}}{{cbignore|bot=medic}}</ref>\n<blockquote>It is naively assumed that the fact that the majority of people share certain ideas or feelings proves the validity of these ideas and feelings. Nothing is further from the truth... Just as there is a ''[[folie \u00e0 deux]]'' there is a ''folie \u00e0 millions''. The fact that millions of people share the same [[vice]]s does not make these vices virtues, the fact that they share so many errors does not make the errors to be truths, and the fact that millions of people share the same form of mental pathology does not make these people sane.<ref>Fromm, Erich. ''The Sane Society'', Routledge, 1955, pp.14\u201315.</ref></blockquote>\n\n== Law ==\nIn [[criminal law|criminal]] and [[mental health law]], sanity is a [[legal term]] denoting that an individual is of sound mind and therefore can bear legal [[Moral responsibility|responsibility]] for their [[Action (philosophy)|actions]]. The official legal term is ''compos mentis''. It is generally defined in terms of the [[wikt:lack|absence]] of insanity (''[[non compos mentis]]'').  It is not a [[medical term]], although the opinions of [[Expert witness|medical expert]]s are often important in making a legal [[Case law|decision]] as to whether someone is sane or insane. It is also not the same concept as [[mental illness]].  One can be acting under profound mental illness and yet be sane, and one can also be [[Court order|ruled]] insane without an underlying mental illness.{{citation needed|date=December 2010}}\n\nLegal definitions of sanity have been little explored by science and medicine, as the concentration has been on illness.{{Citation needed|date=February 2011}} It remains entirely impossible to prove sanity. Furthermore, as Korzybski<ref>Korzybski, A. 2010. ''Selections from Science and Sanity''. The New Non-Aristotelian Library.</ref> has pointed out repeatedly, insanity to various degrees is widespread in the general population, which includes many people that are considered mentally fit in medical and legal terms. In this connection, Erich Fromm<ref>Fromm, Erich. 1955/1990. ''The Sane Society''.</ref> referred to the \"pathology of normalcy,\" while [[David Cooper (psychiatrist)|David Cooper]] proposed that normality was opposed to both madness and sanity.<ref>D Cooper, ''The Death of the Family'' (Penguin 1971) p. 12</ref>\n\n==Literary views==\n*[[J. R. R. Tolkien]] warns us that \"of his own sanity no man may securely judge.\"<ref>Quoted in T A Shippey, ''The Road to Middle Earth'' (London 1992) p. 293</ref>\n\n==See also==\n{{Wikiquote}}\n{{Wiktionary|sane|sanity}}\n* [[George Eman Vaillant]]\n* [[Insanity defense]]\n* [[Rationalism]]\n* [[Sanism]]\n* [[Self-actualisation]]\n\n==References==\n{{More citations needed|date=December 2010}}\n{{Reflist}}\n\n[[Category:Mental health law]]\n[[Category:General semantics]]\n", "name_user": "Cyberbot I", "label": "unsafe", "comment": "(No AfD template, but article isstill at AfD.  Bot adding template. (Peachy 2.0 (alpha 8)))", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Sanity"}
{"title_page": "1883 FA Cup Final", "text_new": "{{Use dmy dates|date=March 2015}}\n{{Use British English|date=March 2015}}\n{{Infobox football match\n| title                   = 1883 FA Cup Final\n| image                   = BlackburnOlympic1883.jpg\n| caption = Blackburn Olympic, winners\n| event                   = [[1882\u201383 FA Cup]]\n| team1                   = [[Blackburn Olympic F.C.|Blackburn Olympic]]\n| team1score              = 2\n| team2                   = [[Old Etonians F.C.|Old Etonians]]\n| team2score              = 1\n| details                 = \n| date                    = 31 March 1883\n| stadium                 = [[Kennington Oval]]\n| city                    = [[London]]\n| man_of_the_match1a      = \n| referee                 = Major Marindin<ref name=SC-Report>{{cite web|url=http://www.sportingchronicle.com/FACUP/1883.html|title=1883 FA Cup Final|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20090513044546/http://www.sportingchronicle.com/FACUP/1883.html|work=Sporting Chronicle|archivedate=13 May 2009|accessdate=26 March 2020}}</ref>\n| attendance              = 8,000<ref name=SC-Report/>\n| weather                 = \n| previous                = [[1882 FA Cup Final|1882]]\n| next                    = [[1884 FA Cup Final|1884]]\n}}\n\nThe '''1883 FA Cup Final''' was contested by [[Blackburn Olympic F.C.|Blackburn Olympic]] and [[Old Etonians F.C.|Old Etonians]] at the [[The Oval|Kennington Oval]]. Blackburn Olympic won 2\u20131 after extra time. [[James Costley]] and Arthur Matthews scored for Blackburn; [[Harry Goodhart]] for Old Etonians. It was a watershed match for the sport, as for the first time in an FA Cup final a [[working-class]] team playing the '[[combination game]]' (passing) were triumphant over a team playing the [[Public school (United Kingdom)|public school]] tactics of '[[Long ball|rushing]]' and '[[Exhibition game|scrimmages]]'.<ref name=WhatIf>{{cite book|title=What If There Had Been No Port In The Vale?: Startling Port Vale Stories!|publisher=Witan Books|date=2011|page=40|isbn=978-0-9529152-8-7}}</ref>\n\n==Overview==\nBlackburn Olympic, coached by former England player, Jack Hunter, had previously eliminated Lower Darwen, Darwen Ramblers and Druids, reaching the final after a 4\u20130 over Old Carthusians in the semi-final. On the other hand, Old Etonians earned to play their third consecutive final, although they were not the favourites to win the match.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.fa-cupfinals.co.uk/1883.html|title=FA Cup Final 1883 - Match Report|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20080521034506/http://www.fa-cupfinals.co.uk/1883.html|work=FA Cup History|archivedate=21 May 2008|accessdate=26 March 2020}}</ref>\n\nThe following is the chronicle of the match, as it appeared on ''[[The Morning Post]]'':\n\n{{cquote\n|text= The deciding trial in the competition came off at Kennington-Oval on Saturday. The attendance was very large. In the first half the Old Etonians scored a goal, kicked by Goodhart, but matters were balanced when Massie got the leather through. At the call of time the score stood at a goal each, and then the extra half-hour was entered upon. A very exciting struggle followed, and at about 15 minutes from the call of time Costley headed the ball through, and no further score being made, Blackburn were winners by two goals to one. The Cup was presented by Major Marindin, and [[Sir William Coddington, 1st Baronet|Mr. Coddington]], [[Member of Parliament (UK)|MP]] for [[Blackburn (UK Parliament constituency)|Blackburn]], acknowledged the compliment on behalf of the winners.\n\nThe Etonians suffere a severe loss through Dunn getting damaged during the first half, but, by way of a set-off, the Blackburn team had three of their men crippled. It was a grandly-contested trial, and the Blackburn men won by fast play and good condition.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://playupliverpool.com/1883/03/31/blackburn-olympic-v-old-etonians-2-1-english-fa-cup-final-march-31-1883/|title= Blackburn Olympic v Old Etonians 2-1 (English FA Cup Final: March 31, 1883|work=Morning Post|via=Play Up Liverpool}}</ref>\n|author = \n|source= ''The Morning Post'' (London), 2 April 1883\n}}\n{{-}}\n\n==Match details==\n{{football box\n|date= 31 March 1883\n|time= \n|event = [[1882\u201383 FA Cup]] \n|team1= [[Blackburn Olympic F.C.|Blackburn Olympic]]\n|score= 2\u20131\n|aet = yes\n|report= [https://web.archive.org/web/20090513044546/http://www.sportingchronicle.com/FACUP/1883.html Report]\n|team2= [[Old Etonians F.C.|Old Etonians]]\n|goals1= {{goal}} Matthews <br> {{goal|107}} [[James Costley|Costley]]\n|goals2= {{goal}} [[Harry Goodhart|Goodhart]]\n|stadium= [[The Oval|Kennington Oval]]\n|attendance= 8,000\n|referee= Major Marindin\n}}\n\n{| width=92%\n|-\n|{{Football kit\n | pattern_la =  \n | pattern_b  = _collar \n | pattern_ra =  \n | pattern_so = \n | leftarm    =  000066\n | body       =  000066\n | rightarm   =  000066\n | shorts     = ffffff \n | socks      = 000066 \n | title      =  Blackburn Olympic\n}}\n|{{Football kit\n | pattern_la = \n | pattern_b  = _collar\n | pattern_ra = \n | pattern_so = \n | leftarm    = ffffff\n | body       = ffffff\n | rightarm   = ffffff\n | shorts     = FFFFFF\n | socks      = 000000\n | title      = Old Etonians\n}}\n|}\n{| style=\"width:100%\"\n|-\n|style=\"vertical-align:top;width:40%\"|\n{| style=\"font-size:90%\" cellspacing=\"0\" cellpadding=\"0\"\n|-\n!width=\"25\"| !!width=\"25\"|\n|-\n|GK || ''' ''' || Thomas Hacking\n|-\n|DF || ''' ''' || [[Jimmy Ward (footballer, born 1865)|James Ward]]  \n|-\n|DF || ''' ''' ||  [[Albert Warburton]]\n|-\n|DF || ''' ''' ||  Thomas Wilson\n|-\n|DF || ''' ''' ||  William Astley\n|-\n|MF || ''' ''' || [[Jack Hunter (footballer)|Jack Hunter]] \n|-\n|FW || ''' ''' || Thomas Dewhurst\n|-\n|FW ||  ''' ''' || [[Fergus Suter]]\n|-\n|FW || ''' ''' || George Wilson \n|-\n|FW || ''' ''' || [[James Costley]] \n|-\n|FW || ''' ''' || [[Jack Yates (footballer, born 1861)|John Yates]] \n|-\n|}\n|valign=\"top\" width=\"50%\"|\n{| cellspacing=\"0\" cellpadding=\"0\" style=\"font-size:90%;margin:auto\"\n|-\n!width=\"25\"| !!width=\"25\"|\n|-\n|-\n|GK || ''' ''' ||  [[John Frederick Peel Rawlinson|John Rawlinson]]\n|-\n|DF || ''' ''' || Thomas French \n|-\n|DF || ''' ''' ||  [[Percy de Paravicini]]\n|-\n|MF || ''' ''' || [[Arthur Kinnaird, 11th Lord Kinnaird|Arthur Kinnaird]] \n|-\n|MF ||''' ''' || Charles Foley \n|-\n|MF ||''' ''' || [[Arthur Dunn]]\n|-\n|FW ||''' ''' || [[Herbert Bainbridge]]\n|-\n|FW || ''' ''' || John Chevallier \n|-\n|FW ||''' ''' || William Anderson \n|-\n|FW ||''' ''' ||   [[Harry Goodhart]]  \n|-\n|FW ||''' ''' ||   [[Reginald Macaulay]] \n|-\n|}\n|}\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n{{FA Cup Finals}}\n{{1882\u201383 in English football}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Fa Cup Final 1883}}\n[[Category:FA Cup Finals|1883]]\n[[Category:1882\u201383 in English football]]\n[[Category:1883 in London]]\n[[Category:March 1883 sports events]]\n", "text_old": "{{Use dmy dates|date=March 2015}}\n{{Use British English|date=March 2015}}\n{{Infobox football match\n| title                   = 1883 FA Cup Final\n| image                   = BlackburnOlympic1883.jpg\n| caption = Blackburn Olympic, winners\n| event                   = [[1882\u201383 FA Cup]]\n| team1                   = [[Blackburn Olympic F.C.|Blackburn Olympic]]\n| team1score              = 2\n| team2                   = [[Old Etonians F.C.|Old Etonians]]\n| team2score              = 1\n| details                 = \n| date                    = 31 March 1883\n| stadium                 = [[Kennington Oval]]\n| city                    = [[London]]\n| man_of_the_match1a      = \n| referee                 = Major Marindin<ref name=SC-Report>{{cite web|url=http://www.sportingchronicle.com/FACUP/1883.html|title=1883 FA Cup Final|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20090513044546/http://www.sportingchronicle.com/FACUP/1883.html|work=Sporting Chronicle|archivedate=13 May 2009|accessdate=26 March 2020}}</ref>\n| attendance              = 8,000<ref name=SC-Report/>\n| weather                 = \n| previous                = [[1882 FA Cup Final|1882]]\n| next                    = [[1884 FA Cup Final|1884]]\n}}\n\nThe '''1883 FA Cup Final''' was contested by [[Blackburn Olympic F.C.|Blackburn Olympic]] and [[Old Etonians F.C.|Old Etonians]] at the [[The Oval|Kennington Oval]]. Blackburn Olympic won 2\u20131 after extra time. [[James Costley]] and Arthur Matthews scored for Blackburn; [[Harry Goodhart]] for Old Etonians. It was a watershed match for the sport, as for the first time in an FA Cup final a [[working-class]] team playing the '[[combination game]]' (passing) were triumphant over a team playing the [[Public school (United Kingdom)|public school]] tactics of '[[Long ball|rushing]]' and '[[Exhibition game|scrimmages]]'.<ref name=WhatIf>{{cite book|title=What If There Had Been No Port In The Vale?: Startling Port Vale Stories!|publisher=Witan Books|date=2011|page=40|isbn=978-0-9529152-8-7}}</ref>\n\n==Overview==\nBlackburn Olympic, coached by former England player, Jack Hunter, had previously eliminated Lower Darwen, Darwen Ramblers and Druids, reaching the final after a 4\u20130 over Old Carthusians in the semi-final. On the other hand, Old Etonians earned to play their third consecutive final, although they were not the favourites to win the match.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.fa-cupfinals.co.uk/1883.html|title=FA Cup Final 1883 - Match Report|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20080521034506/http://www.fa-cupfinals.co.uk/1883.html|work=FA Cup History|archivedate=21 May 2008|accessdate=26 March 2020}}</ref>\n\nThe following is the chronicle of the match, as it appeared on ''[[The Morning Post]]'':\n\n{{cquote\n|text= The deciding trial in the competition came off at Kennington-Oval on Saturday. The attendance was very large. In the first half the Old Etonians scored a goal, kicked by Goodhart, but matters were balanced when Massie got the leather through. At the call of time the score stood at a goal each, and then the extra half-hour was entered upon. A very exciting struggle followed, and at about 15 minutes from the call of time Costley headed the ball through, and no further score being made, Blackburn were winners by two goals to one. The Cup was presented by Major Marindin, and [[Sir William Coddington, 1st Baronet|Mr. Coddington]], [[Member of Parliament (UK)|MP]] for [[Blackburn (UK Parliament constituency)|Blackburn]], acknowledged the compliment on behalf of the winners.\n\nThe Etonians suffere a severe loss through Dunn getting damaged during the first half, but, by way of a set-off, the Blackburn team had three of their men crippled. It was a grandly-contested trial, and the Blackburn men won by fast play and good condition.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://playupliverpool.com/1883/03/31/blackburn-olympic-v-old-etonians-2-1-english-fa-cup-final-march-31-1883/|title= Blackburn Olympic v Old Etonians 2-1 (English FA Cup Final: March 31, 1883|work=Morning Post|via=Play Up Liverpool}}</ref>\n|author = \n|source= ''The Morning Post'' (London), 2 April 1883\n}}\n{{-}}\n\n==Match details==\n{{football box\n|date= 31 March 1883\n|time= \n|event = [[1882\u201383 FA Cup]] \n|team1= [[Blackburn Olympic F.C.|Blackburn Olympic]]\n|score= 2\u20131\n|aet = yes\n|report= [https://web.archive.org/web/20090513044546/http://www.sportingchronicle.com/FACUP/1883.html Report]\n|team2= [[Old Etonians F.C.|Old Etonians]]\n|goals1= {{goal}} Matthews <br> {{goal|107}} [[James Costley|Costley]]\n|goals2= {{goal}} [[Harry Goodhart|Goodhart]]\n|stadium= [[The Oval|Kennington Oval]]\n|attendance= 8,000\n|referee= Major Marindin\n}}\n\n{| width=92%\n|-\n|{{Football kit\n | pattern_la =  \n | pattern_b  = _collar \n | pattern_ra =  \n | pattern_so = \n | leftarm    =  000066\n | body       =  000066\n | rightarm   =  000066\n | shorts     = ffffff \n | socks      = 000066 \n | title      =  Blackburn Olympic\n}}\n|{{Football kit\n | pattern_